SIMPLE: torpid
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Torpid
<hw>Tor"pid</hw> <pr>(t⟦ocir⟧r"p⟦icr⟧d)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>torpidus</ets>, fr. <ets>torpere</ets> to be stiff, numb, or
torpid; of uncertain origin.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having lost motion,
or the power of exertion and feeling; numb; benumbed; <as>as, a
<ex>torpid</ex> limb</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Without heat all things would be <qex>torpid</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Ray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Dull; stupid; sluggish; inactive.</def> <rj><au>Sir
M. Hale.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Torpid</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Torpid
<hw>Tor"pid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Torpid</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <mark>[Slang, Oxford University, Eng.]</mark>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>An inferior racing boat, or one who rows in such a
boat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The Lenten rowing races.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Torpidity</ent>⟦br⟧
